LEPROSY - PHILIPPINES
*********************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 9 Nov 2015
Source: ABS-CBN News [edited]
http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/focus/11/09/15/ph-tops-in-new-cases-of-leprosy-in-west-pacific-who


"Is there any person here who [knows someone who] has died of leprosy?" This was the question posed by Hilarion Guia to international and Philippine government health officials and specialists at the 2nd International Leprosy Stakeholders Symposium in Manila. The answer to Guia's question might as well be "no" since deaths from leprosy are very rare.

Guia was diagnosed with leprosy as a young boy. He is already cured from the disease but the deformities and missing fingers in his hand bear the scars of a painful past. He was treated in the "land of the living dead" in Culion, Palawan, which was known as the country's "leper colony."

But now, things have changed. Culion is becoming a tourist area especially for beach lovers. In fact, Guia was the 1st mayor of Culion and is currently the president of the Coalition of Leprosy Advocates in the Philippines. "Culion Island is leprosy-free. Leprosy has been totally controlled," claimed Guia.

But leprosy still exists in the Philippines. World Health Organization (WHO) Regional Office for the Western Pacific's coordinator for Stop TB [tuberculosis] and Leprosy Elimination, Dr Nobuyuki Nishikiori, reported that there were 1655 new cases of leprosy in the country in 2014. This was the highest in the Western Pacific Region. China came 2nd with 823, and 3rd was Papua New Guinea with 540 new cases in 2014.

Dr Ernesto Villalon head of the National Leprosy Program of the Department of Health (DOH) said that most of the leprosy cases were reported to come from Region 7 or Central Visayas, which covers Cebu, Bohol, Negros, and Bicol. Dr Villalon said that majority of the cases came from Cebu, which has the biggest leprosy and TB facility but it doesn't mean they are from Cebu. "Some of them come to Cebu and they do not say where they originally come from for fear of discrimination," he said.

Health Undersecretary Vicente Belizario called for identifying the remaining "pockets" or "barangays" with reported leprosy cases and to look for solutions not just highlight the challenges. Dr Villalon said that they are now in the process of collating data and will soon be able to identify the remaining small units.

"Leprosy is something we should push forward harder now. We should move forward from disease control and prevention towards elimination," said Belizario. But Dr Nishikiori stressed that there is a tendency to sometimes confuse "elimination with sustainability. We tend to focus on elimination, [and] we might eliminate the programs and services. Elimination is the result. What is also important is sustainable services," said Nishikiori.

Leprosy is curable and treatment is free in the Philippines. The multi-drug therapy (MDT) to treat leprosy is given for free in government hospitals.

[Byline: Nina Corpuz]

