ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Philippines, with an estimated population of over 100 million residents in 2015, is an archipelago of 7107 islands that are divided into 3 island groups: Luzon, Visayas, and Mindanao, which are further divided into the Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM), 17 regions, and 81 provinces (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philippines; https://shairasaloma005.files.wordpress.com/2014/09/aaa.png.

Culion, an island in the Palawan province of the Philippines, was established at the beginning of the 20th century by the US government in order to rid leprosy from the Philippine islands through isolating all existing cases (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Culion_leper_colony).

The Philippines is in the Western Pacific Region, one of the 6 regions of WHO (regional map at http://hiip.wpro.who.int/portal/portals/0/CountryProfiles/Western_Pacific_Region.png). The Western Pacific Region is home to about 1.6 billion people, nearly 1/3 of the world's population. This region includes 37 countries and areas, from China and Mongolia in the north and west, to New Zealand and Australia in the south, to Japan and Korea in the north east, and to French Polynesia in the south east (http://www.wpro.who.int/countries/en/). Also included are Brunei, Cambodia, Laos, Malaysia, Papua New Guinea, Singapore; and Viet Nam, plus multiple smaller Pacific island countries, in addition to the Philippines (http://www.wpro.who.int/countries/en/).

The National Leprosy Control Program in the Philippines was established in 1986 and leprosy has been eliminated in the Philippines as a public health problem at the national level (that is, a prevalence of less than 1 case per 10 000 population) in 1998, although there are pockets of cases around the country. In 1986, the leprosy prevalence rate was 7.2 per 10 000 population and in 2010, the prevalence rate was down to 0.31 due to the nationwide implementation of multidrug therapy and other tactics (http://www.wpro.who.int/philippines/areas/communicable_diseases/leprosy/who_leprosy_control_burden_.pdf).

However, the Philippines had more new cases reported than any of the other countries in the Western Pacific region and the number of new cases in the Philippines comprised 40.4 percent of that of the Western Pacific Region in 2010 (http://www.wpro.who.int/philippines/areas/communicable_diseases/leprosy/who_leprosy_control_burden_.pdf), but the incidence rate (the number of cases per 100 000 population) are 50 to 100-fold higher in Micronesia, Kiribati, and the Marshall Islands.

The percent of new cases detected in the Philippines that are multibacillary, the contagious form of the disease, was high at 94 percent, indicating a high potential for transmission and risk for complications that can increase the disabilities; but the percent of new cases detected in children below 15 years old remained low at 4.6 percent, indicating low ongoing transmission. - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3782359,158.]
